reviews_data.review_text:
From the early 10's for years I spent a lot of time in the Camden and central avenue locations.
I think it's a place that has charm, it's unique, and it has awesome food.
Walking in, feels like you're somewhere that's inherently connected to Charlotte. It always was, and does even today at this new location.
To me, it's one of the most significant institutions of this citys culture.

It was a shock to try this new location since the move, and feel like I'd never been in common market before. The setup is spacious, streamlined, and very utilitarian.
As opposed to years past, the offerings seem like an afterthought, with a primary focus on efficiency and entertainment.
It's a welcome placement amidst the breweries and various libations; as it has a charming simplicity.
The food is without flaws. Generous servings, quick service, good hot food.
A perfect accompaniment to a nice cold beer and good friends.

Love comming here on my days off to hang out! They have non alcoholic options THC options snacks a deli, outside seating and inside/balcony options. Come check it out if u haven’t already get the Sinatra sandwich from the deli so fire !!!!

Pretty good Philly Cheesesteak and great fries!! Nice patio to hang out and nice decor inside.

All the staff are so kind and helpful. I ordered the weekend special - Pimp My Bowl - and it was delicious. Then I ordered the falafel wrap to go so I can enjoy it later. Thanks guys for a great Sunday lunch experience.

reviews_data.review_text:
i’ve been holding back on writing this review for almost a month because i used to enjoy common market (except for the oakhurst location) but i really thought they should be aware of this.

me and two of my friends went to common market on february 8th sometime between 5 and 5:30pm to grab a bite close to the train station before seeing aespa at spectrum. it had been a while since i’d been to this location and i was with people who had never been, so we looked over the menu quickly before going up to the counter and ordering…

only to be told we can’t order from that menu? we were given another, much smaller menu instead. weird, but sometimes things are. one of my friends tried to order a simple salad, told they can’t do that. again, weird, but by then i was getting annoyed. i work in food service so i try to have sympathy for other workers, but it’s a damn SALAD, it’s not that difficult! i ordered the bánh mì with tofu, and i had to show the person at the counter that it literally says it’s an option in the description after they said they can’t do that!

i genuinely don’t mean to be rude, but the person at the counter seemed like they had no idea what they were doing. they were very nice (i got my sandwich for free with my punch card), but they were completely out of it lol.

i was trying to show off a food spot i like in front of my friends but ended up feeling like an idiot. i guess common market isn’t doing so well… rock hill closed, oakhurst took away of their good vegan options, and now southend sucks? sad to see a cool place go so downhill.
The Fire Inside and Good Hair Day is the breakfast of champions! 🌞

reviews_data.review_text: This venue is very cool.  The decor provides a nice atmosphere. There are many different places to sit. We were very disappointed with the food. My husband ordered a Dilworth sandwich at $12. You can see from the picture how little meat is in it. Nice bun though.  I ordered a CBRBLT. This sandwich was fresh and bland. We will probably eat before we come again, if we come again.
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Thanks for your feedback Deme.  We can understand your disappointment  that the sandwich did not meet your expectations.  We strive hard to create great sandwiches and at times we can fall short of expectations.  The size of our ciabatta bread is often time inconsistent, and something we are actively working with our supplier on.  We weigh out all of our meat portions and unfortunately with oversized bread it can make the portions appear smaller at times.

In this case, we appreciate you bringing this to the attention of both our manager and employee in the store.  We offered to remake the sandwich in this instance, but your partner declined that offer.  We were happy to refund this sandwich and offer you a free sandwich for your next visit and hope to see you again.

reviews_data.review_text: Great place to grab a sandwich and drink while enjoying some music.

I really want to love this place but the breakfast menu is just not good. The sandwich is a 2/10, soggy and tasteless. Ordered a side of turkey sausage and they give you one and a half (yes half) super small pieces for $4. They need to scrap the entire menu and get inspired, have some pride in what you put out the pickup window! Hire me as a consultant to show you how to make a bomb breakfast burrito. Do something!The atmosphere is fun and the location is A+. Extra star for big buck HD.

Edit: Tacked on another star for the reply, thanks
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Thanks for stopping by BW.  I am sorry to hear that your breakfast sandwich was not up to your satisfaction.  I am curious if you addressed this with an employee onsite to see if we could make any corrective measures to ensure you were satisfied? We do have a breakfast burrito on our menu that is the most popular breakfast item - The Fire Inside - so if you do give us another chance, that may be a good item to try.  Thanks again!

At the bar, the staff are kind and do a wonderful job - balancing giving patrons space while also being attentive. To a person, the day-to-day bartenders and staff members are superb, and I cannot say enough good things about them 🫶

I say that to say there’s a special atmosphere at Common Market - if we can, let’s preserve the moment and keep commercialism/corporatism at bay 😊

reviews_data.review_text: Went here after multiple  bad experiences with Einstein Brothers Bagels because a friend suggested I come here because they also serve breakfast. I didn’t know what to expect, but everything about this place is quite cool. The staff is friendly and helpful and I think that positive energy even translates to the overall experience and makes other customers more pleasant. I only went here for breakfast but after looking at the menu I decided to get something for lunch. The prices are comparable to Einstein brothers bagels probably cheaper but the portions are bigger and the options are a bit more unique which I like. It’s nice to walk in somewhere and find something so unexpected. The decor is also really cool. I love how every where you turn there is something fun to look at or read that makes this place very unique in comparison to many of the other places surrounded by the area. It’s like a market and dive bar combined with a retail store. I love it. I’ll definitely be coming back and bringing some friends with me. Also they have a rewards program so that’s pretty cool. Also the god is pretty good too. If you’re looking for somewhere different, fun, but relaxed and somewhat nostalgic and familiar I recommend this place.

reviews_data.review_text: Love the food, selection of beers, and atmosphere. However, their deli does not serve after 5PM. Also, i went in to grab a sandwich and noticed around 8 customers who were waiting for their food. While they had two people working in back, one was busting his butt trying to make sandwiches,  while the other was doing prep-work, instead of helping. Also, why would a deli not be open for the dinner hour?
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hey, Christopher, thank you for your feedback. As an FYI, we were a little short-handed when you came in yesterday. If you see one guy crushing sandwiches and one prepping and “not helping out”, it is most likely because that prep is necessary in order to make sandwiches that are hanging on the board to be made. Such is the chaos of our industry! And, to be sure, anytime you come in to our deli at noon, there will most likely be a little bit of a wait. Any place that serves good food will have one. To be sure, with the short staff, we may have run some longer ticket times than usual but that is certainly not the standard.

In terms of the dinner service, we do actually serve food after 5pm - just not from our regular menu!  We have recently changed things up and now a new "Night Food" menu starting at 5 pm Tuesday through Saturday at our Southend location (and soon to follow at Oakwold!). On those days, from 5 pm – 9 pm, we are serving from our “Street Food Pop-up” menu. This week and last week we served latino street foods from the kitchen at Southend. Our menu included, sweet plantains, tacos, arepas, tamales and tortas. Next week we will be doing Vietnamese street foods. (Monday nights you will still see the regular deli menu).

The impetus behind this decision was multi-faceted. Primarily it is a response to sluggish evening sales. What we have found, in general, is that most of our evening crowd is there to hang out and socialize – which we love. The Common Market is a proud hub for community activities. Most of our food sales were centering around items that people could share which, for now, are items from out cold box like hummus and pimento cheese with crackers or chips. We recognized the success our Commonwealth location had with serving Drew’s Thai menu there in the evenings and decided to replicate their business hours in order to build a more consistent business model. Our street food menus are flavor-focused items, some exotic and some familiar, that pair well against our tap and are shareable. The folks that have tried our new menu selections in the past week have given us some great feedback and we are excited about exploring a whole new culinary landscape through our kitchens at Oakwold and Southend. We hope you can be a part of that journey, too!

reviews_data.review_text: Love this little gem in South End! We love to come here after climbing at Inner Peaks. You can get a quick, tasty dinner when you're HUNGRY and aren't in the mood to wait 2 hours for a table or spend a ton of money (but the deli closes earlier than the bar!). They have awesome salads - my favorites are the Cobb and the Scoop (large for a filling post-gym dinner!) I love the excellent protein choices. The salad dressings are excellent and many are homemade. The guys in the deli are always super nice even when one of us can't seem to make up our minds on what to order :-) I've only had a sandwich once - we shared a grilled BLT and that was just right for me. It definitely didn't taste healthy ;-) (Now if we can just remember to use our frequent flyer card every time...) I love that the bar has an ever rotating selection of beers and specials on Mon/Wed. It's a great place to find/try a new favorite craft beer. They bartenders are nice and let us sample so we find just the right one! The interior is interesting and fun. Overall, I love the friendly staff and the quality of the food. It's a low stress, low key, fun place to hang out.

reviews_data.owner_answer:
Thanks for the feedback on our sandwiches Joseph! It would help us gauge your feedback if you could provide us with a little more information. What sandwich did you have? Did you enjoy the sandwich?

The struggle for choosing a price point for food that reflects the actual cost of the ingredients while being financially sustainable is one that every restaurant contends with. Many things affect the decision. There are formulas we fall back on but ultimately our goal is provide a value to our guests. In every restaurant I’ve worked in, people have asked me, “Why does X dish cost so much?” My reply as of late has been, “A better question is, “Why is that other food so cheap?”

If all we were concerned with was the bottom line we could certainly use cheaper meats and cheese, buy bread for our sandwiches from a giant food conglomerate rather than support a local bakery – buy caged eggs rather than support a local farm etc. But our choices reflect the core values we support. We source our foods responsibly, we support small local businesses and we treat our employees well. All of our foods, soups and sauces are made from scratch.  All of this affects our final product, what we need to charge for it and how we serve it.

I hope this provides some context for the hows and whys of what we (and other restaurants) charge for their food. We’d love to hear back from you on some more specific details of your experience to see what we can do to increase the value of our product in your eyes. Thanks in advance for any other feedback you can provide and we look forward to hearing from you and, hopefully, serving you again in the future.

Thanks for your feedback Deme.  We can understand your disappointment  that the sandwich did not meet your expectations.  We strive hard to create great sandwiches and at times we can fall short of expectations. reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hey, Christopher, thank you for your feedback. As an FYI, we were a little short-handed when you came in yesterday. If you see one guy crushing sandwiches and one prepping and “not helping out”, it is most likely because that prep is necessary in order to make sandwiches that are hanging on the board to be made. Such is the chaos of our industry! And, to be sure, anytime you come in to our deli at noon, there will most likely be a little bit of a wait. Any place that serves good food will have one. To be sure, with the short staff, we may have run some longer ticket times than usual but that is certainly not the standard.

In terms of the dinner service, we do actually serve food after 5pm - just not from our regular menu!  We have recently changed things up and now a new "Night Food" menu starting at 5 pm Tuesday through Saturday at our Southend location (and soon to follow at Oakwold!). On those days, from 5 pm – 9 pm, we are serving from our “Street Food Pop-up” menu. This week and last week we served latino street foods from the kitchen at Southend. Our menu included, sweet plantains, tacos, arepas, tamales and tortas. Next week we will be doing Vietnamese street foods. (Monday nights you will still see the regular deli menu).

The impetus behind this decision was multi-faceted. Primarily it is a response to sluggish evening sales. What we have found, in general, is that most of our evening crowd is there to hang out and socialize – which we love. The Common Market is a proud hub for community activities. Most of our food sales were centering around items that people could share which, for now, are items from out cold box like hummus and pimento cheese with crackers or chips. We recognized the success our Commonwealth location had with serving Drew’s Thai menu there in the evenings and decided to replicate their business hours in order to build a more consistent business model. Our street food menus are flavor-focused items, some exotic and some familiar, that pair well against our tap and are shareable. The folks that have tried our new menu selections in the past week have given us some great feedback and we are excited about exploring a whole new culinary landscape through our kitchens at Oakwold and Southend. We hope you can be a part of that journey, too!

reviews_data.owner_answer:
Thanks for the feedback on our sandwiches Joseph! It would help us gauge your feedback if you could provide us with a little more information. What sandwich did you have? Did you enjoy the sandwich?

The struggle for choosing a price point for food that reflects the actual cost of the ingredients while being financially sustainable is one that every restaurant contends with. Many things affect the decision. There are formulas we fall back on but ultimately our goal is provide a value to our guests. In every restaurant I’ve worked in, people have asked me, “Why does X dish cost so much?” My reply as of late has been, “A better question is, “Why is that other food so cheap?”

If all we were concerned with was the bottom line we could certainly use cheaper meats and cheese, buy bread for our sandwiches from a giant food conglomerate rather than support a local bakery – buy caged eggs rather than support a local farm etc. But our choices reflect the core values we support. We source our foods responsibly, we support small local businesses and we treat our employees well. All of our foods, soups and sauces are made from scratch.  All of this affects our final product, what we need to charge for it and how we serve it.

I hope this provides some context for the hows and whys of what we (and other restaurants) charge for their food. We’d love to hear back from you on some more specific details of your experience to see what we can do to increase the value of our product in your eyes. Thanks in advance for any other feedback you can provide and we look forward to hearing from you and, hopefully, serving you again in the future.
